      Good times
   =20
 =20
One thing that happened at Goldman Sachs Group Inc. in 2021 is that a group=
 of junior analysts  put together a  PowerPoint presentation for their mana=
gers, which subsequently went viral online, about how miserable they were f=
rom working so hard. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve been through foster care and thi=
s is arguably worse,=E2=80=9D said one analyst. Other big financial firms r=
eceived similar complaints. Everyone was working really hard and they did n=
ot like it.Another thing that happened at Goldman in 2021 is that it made s=
o much money, and its competitors made so much money, that it paid its seni=
or bankers and traders tens of millions of dollars in bonuses and special e=
xtra bonuses. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0 Sridhar Natarajan and Hannah Levitt=
 report:Wall Streeters are buzzing about the swelling number of people scor=
ing eight-figure pay packages this year. The top earners at Goldman will be=
 approaching $30 million, with some even exceeding that mark, people famili=
ar with the matter have said. Those rewards included=C2=A0special one-time =
payouts=C2=A0for a few hundred top executives.=C2=A0And at=C2=A0Jefferies F=
inancial Group Inc., pay for some of the best performers has surpassed $25 =
million, people with knowledge of the matter said. There=E2=80=99s a notabl=
e feature: Executives can elect to get paid in cash, unlike the stock-heavy=
 compensation at larger rivals.The article goes on to talk about Tribeca pe=
nthouse apartments, thousand-dollar Barolos and Goldman Chief Executive Off=
icer and DJ David Solomon being =E2=80=9Cscheduled to hit the DJ circuit ag=
ain in sunny Los Angeles this month at an event billed as the =E2=80=98elit=
e playground of partygoers.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9DThese things are related! Wall=
 Street is making a lot of money because it is busy; Wall Street is paying =
people a lot of money because they are busy. (Strictly, it is paying its se=
nior rainmakers a lot of money because they are doing a good job of keeping=
 the junior analysts busy, which is probably more pleasant for the rainmake=
rs than it is for the analysts.)=C2=A0Merger and issuance and trading=C2=A0=
activity are booming, and loosely speaking the way that big Wall Street ban=
ks get paid is by (1) intermediating securities and derivatives trades and =
taking a spread and (2) advising companies on mergers, acquisitions and sto=
ck and bond issuance and taking a fee. They are middlemen, service provider=
s, and as markets are ebullient and volatile there is a lot of demand for t=
heir services.None of this is unusual; this is also how law firms work, or =
Starbucks, or really any other business. If there is a lot of client demand=
 you work hard to meet it and you make a lot of money. Wall Street has a ce=
rtain extra leverage because it deals in piles of money: It costs Starbucks=
 roughly 10 times as much effort to make 10 times as many coffees, for whic=
h it earns roughly=C2=A010 times as much money; it does not cost Goldman th=
at much more effort to do a $10 billion merger than=C2=A0a $1 billion merge=
r, but the $10 billion merger does bring in much higher fees.=C2=A0Still th=
e money varies in some rough proportion to the workload.There are =E2=80=A6=
=C2=A0other kinds of finance? Kinds that are less about providing client se=
rvice? Certainly if you took your modest Goldman bonus in 2012, invested al=
l of it in Bitcoin and played video games for the last decade, you=E2=80=99=
d be richer now than if you spent that decade working 100-hour weeks at Gol=
dman and becoming a $30-million-a-year superstar.[1] I think a lot of peopl=
e at Goldman are keenly aware of that. There is a sense in the traditional =
financial intermediation business, the working-on-behalf-of-clients busines=
s that the big banks are in,=C2=A0that the money is at least somewhat a fun=
ction of effort, and that in other corners of the world that connection is =
less tight:Back in 2007, the head of Goldman Sachs was one of the highest-p=
aid executives in the broadest definition of Wall Street. Today, when it co=
mes to pay, banks occupy a relatively impoverished corner of the financial =
metaverse. Private equity firms dole out far more to their leaders. And the=
n there=E2=80=99s the riches being minted at Silicon Valley ventures and in=
 cryptocurrencies.=E2=80=9CIn different eras, Wall Street really stood out =
alone,=E2=80=9D Corzine said. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s not the case now.=E2=
=80=9DLast month  I quoted the line in =E2=80=9CLiar=E2=80=99s Poker=E2=80=
=9D in which Michael Lewis, on his first day as a bond salesman at Salomon =
Brothers, says =E2=80=9CI didn=E2=80=99t really imagine I was going to work=
, more as if I were going to collect lottery winnings.=E2=80=9D That is not=
 how the junior people feel now! Now it=E2=80=99s worse than foster care! N=
ow they see=C2=A0other=C2=A0people getting rich in ways that look more like=
 lottery winnings.One thing to do, when faced with this situation, is to au=
tomate the business of financial intermediation, so that you can scale up t=
he revenue without doing too much more work. Another class of financial int=
ermediaries was perhaps even busier than the big banks in 2021. The Wall St=
reet Journal reports:Brokerages serving individual investors received a win=
dfall last year for selling their customers=E2=80=99 order flow to electron=
ic trading firms, even as the practice faced increasing scrutiny from regul=
ators.The dozen largest U.S. brokerages earned a combined $3.8 billion for =
selling their customers=E2=80=99 stock and options orders last year, up 33%=
 from 2020, according to new data compiled by Bloomberg Intelligence and re=
leased Tuesday. =E2=80=A6Citadel Securities continued to be the biggest sou=
rce of payment for order flow. The electronic trading giant founded by hedg=
e-fund billionaire Ken Griffin paid the 12 brokerages tracked by Bloomberg =
just under $1.5 billion for order flow last year, the data show. Other larg=
e sources of the payments were Susquehanna International Group LLP and Wolv=
erine Trading LLC, a pair of low-profile trading firms that are significant=
 players in options markets.It seems safe to say that Citadel Securities ma=
de a whole ton of money from intermediating all those trades. It also seems=
 safe to say that people at Citadel Securities were=C2=A0busier=C2=A0during=
 the meme-stock boom than they otherwise would have been: They had some lat=
e-night phone calls with Robinhood and so forth. But there was not some 23-=
year-old analyst at Citadel Securities frantically working the phones to do=
 all those trades. The computers did those trades. Citadel Securities is in=
 the business of=C2=A0automating=C2=A0stock and options trading for retail =
clients; as markets get busier Citadel Securities gets richer but its life =
doesn=E2=80=99t get that much more unpleasant.That is how tech companies ar=
e supposed to work, scaling up not with labor but with technology, and Cita=
del Securities has recently  attracted venture-capital investment as more o=
r less a tech company. The big banks have also been fond, in recent years, =
of saying that they are tech companies, and of  rolling out  apps to automa=
te bits of their financial-intermediation offerings. =C2=A0There is a huge =
gusher of money in financial intermediation right now, but you have to pay =
a lot of people to stand in front of it with buckets and laboriously haul=
=C2=A0it away. The money is nice, but it would be better if there were an e=
asier way.
