s busy; Wall Street is paying people a lot of money because they are busy. =
(Strictly, it is paying its senior rainmakers a lot of money because they a=
re doing a good job of keeping the junior analysts busy, which is probably =
more pleasant for the rainmakers than it is for the analysts.)=C2=A0Merger =
and issuance and trading=C2=A0activity are booming, and loosely speaking th=
e way that big Wall Street banks get paid is by (1) intermediating securiti=
es and derivatives trades and taking a spread and (2) advising companies on=
 mergers, acquisitions and stock and bond issuance and taking a fee. They a=
re middlemen, service providers, and as markets are ebullient and volatile =
there is a lot of demand for their services.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">None of this is unusual; this is also how law firms work, or Starbucks, o=
r really any other business. If there is a lot of client demand you work ha=
