 decade, you=E2=80=99d be richer now than if you spent that decade working =
100-hour weeks at Goldman and becoming a $30-million-a-year superstar.[1] I=
 think a lot of people at Goldman are keenly aware of that. There is a sens=
e in the traditional financial intermediation business, the working-on-beha=
lf-of-clients business that the big banks are in,=C2=A0that the money is at=
 least somewhat a function of effort, and that in other corners of the worl=
d that connection is less tight:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">Back in 2007, the head of Goldman Sachs was one of the highest-paid execu=
