olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">essentially infinitesimal units</a>; for one U.S. cent you can buy =
about 2,654 atomic one-one-hundred-millionth fractions of a Bitcoin, which =
is probably enough precision for any reasonable purpose. You can convert an=
y amount of dollars into Bitcoins,=C2=A0there is no real discontinuity wher=
e 1 Bitcoin is vastly better than 0.9999 Bitcoins, and the nominal expensiv=
eness of Bitcoin has no practical importance.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">And yet this objection is not uncommon. You sometimes hear people say th=
at they like some other cryptocurrency more than Bitcoin=C2=A0because the p=
rice of Bitcoin is off-putting, not in some fundamental-valuation sense but=
 just in the sense that a $30,000+ price tag for anything will scare people=
 off. People prefer to buy things where one whole thing costs a normal amou=
nt of money, even if the concept =E2=80=9Cone whole thing=E2=80=9D makes no=
 sense and has no practical importance.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">I used to vaguely think that the rise of crypto, with its visibly arbitr=
ary prices and its=C2=A0microscopic fractionalization of everything, would =
change this preference, but it has not. Specifically I used to vaguely thin=
k that <em>stock splits=C2=A0</em>would be less of a thing: If everyone und=
erstands that a $30,000+ price tag for Bitcoin is arbitrary and you can buy=
 whatever fraction of a Bitcoin you want, then everyone will get used to th=
e fact that a $2,700+ price tag for Alphabet Inc. common stock is arbitrary=
 and you can buy whatever fraction of an Alphabet share you want.[3] (At le=
ast you can now that retail brokerages <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/26573728.257620/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
